track ordering now always uses bipartite matching algorithm, no longer assumes current metadata to be correct if it's completePreviously, we were using the Munkres algorithm (minimum bipartite matching) tonorder tracks intelligently only as a fallback if the current metadata wasnparadoxical or incomplete. This was because of a concern about the performancenof the potentially-O(n^3) Munkres solver. However, it was found that (a) thenperformance is actually not bad, taking on the order of 0.02 to perform anmatching, and (b) there was no recourse for the tagger to reorder tracks thatnwere legitimately in the wrong order. Now, we get intelligent reordering ofnbadly tagged music even when the metadata seems to be complete.nnTo retain some of the functionality of the old orderer, the track distancenmetric was expanded to include a component reflecting the track index.nnIn doing this, another bug was discovered in the UI that showed the track namendifferences based on an arbitrary ordering. Now, the tag_album function returnsna reordered items list with every candidate.n

use None instead of pipeline.BUBBLE to indicate skipsThis makes the apply_choices coroutine run even for albums that are skipped ornstill in the library. reliably terminate pipeline when exception is raisedPreviously, the producer thread (i.e., the first stage) would continue runningnto completion even when an exception was raised! And, depending on the size ofnthe queue, deadlock was even possible if the next stage was no longer consumingnthe produced values.n
make pipeline exceptions look more natural

don't bother poisoning the queue on exceptionPreviously, we tried to shut down everything very nicely by sending along anchannel poison message when an exception occurred. That, of course, wasndisastrous because some of the pipeline was no longer running and the poisonnwas unlikely to get all the way through. Now we just abort every thread andnclear every queue (to force the abort even when blocking on enqueues). Thisnproblem manifested as a deadlock when an exception occurred in the finalnstage.n

deal with invalid pathname encodingsSo. Apparently, os.listdir() will *try* to give you Unicode when you give itnUnicode, but will occasionally give you bytestrings when it can't decode anfilename. Also, I've now had two separate reports from users whose filesystemsnreport a UTF-8 filesystem encoding but whose files contain latin1 characters.nThe choices were to (a) switch over to bytestrings entirely for filenames orn(b) just deal with the badly-encoded filenames. Option (a) is very unattractivenbecause it requires me to store bytestrings in sqlite (which is not onlyncomplicated but would require more code to deal with legacy databases) andncomplicates the construction of pathnames from (Unicode) metadata. Therefore,nI've implemented a static fallback to latin1 if the default pathname decodenfails. Furthermore, if that also fails, the _sorted_walk function just ignoresnthe badly-encoded file (and logs an error).n

fixed pause & resume, which neither paused nor resumedIn the multithreaded version, the directory done state was written beforenother progress states, causing it to be overwritten. This was because I hadnstupidly put the done message in the initial generator, which of coursenfinishes before the entire pipeline finished. This manifested as two problems:nthe tagger would always want to resume even when it had finished the lastntime; aBorting the process would not cause the next run to resume.n

revert a silly decision about hard-coding latin1Decoding a path as latin1 when it appears undecodable is a non-solutionnbecause, the next time we want to actually *use* the path, it will be encodedndifferently and the file won't be found. Death to undecodable paths!n

all paths are now bytestrings (not unicode)In the end, after all of this, it turns out that we basically need to abandonnthe temptation of dealing with unicode paths altogether. The POSIX filesystemnAPI has no notion of unicode and is very much a bytes-only interface. Thisnmeans that undecodable pathnames are a reality we must deal with. This newnapproach stores all paths as buffers (blobs) in SQLite and -- as transparentlynas possible -- presents them as str objects to the Python code. Legacyndatabases will have their paths automatically encoded into str objects, andnwill lazily have their unicodes in the database replaced with buffers.n

make result iterators query the database eagerly (#261)Previously, ResultIterators would query the database lazily. Specifically, theynwould only fetch a row from the underlying cursor when an Item was pulled fromnthe iterator. This was a performance optimization. However, it was causingnendless headaches due to SQLite's locking policy: as long as the cursor isnopen, it holds a reader lock. This led to many hard-to-diagnose problems whenntrying to acquire a writer lock. This solution may require a little more memory,nbut it should put an end to this kind of bug for good.n

autotag: Can now compute the distance for incomplete albumsIf the user has some songs from a specific album, but not all of them,nthe real solution is immediately discarded. This commit is the first of anseries that will implement support for these incomplete albums.nnThe point of this patch is to make sure missing commits are taken intonaccount when calculating the distance between an album and its canonicalndata.nnNote that in order not to break API compatibility, the album_distancencall for the plugins receives a purged version of both the items and thenalbum info, resulting in some potential accuracy if the plugin basesnitself on the index of a track in album_info.tracks.n

autotag: Fill the blanks when ordering incomplete albumIn the function order_items, instead of automatically reject thencanonical candidate if it has more tracks, the function still tries tonfind matches for the tracks amongst the items, and otherwise uses Nonento fill the void in order to keep the information about the tracknnumbersn

never invalidate a queue with NoneI saw this *extremely* intermittently (and wasn't able to reproduce it at all),nbut I think there was a race when invalidating an output queue in the abort()nmethod of PipelineThread. It was possible for a thread's input queue to beninvalidated (with val=None) while abort_flag was False (and abort_lock was notnheld). This would cause coroutines to see a None value when the pipeline wasnshutting down. Always poisoning a queue when it's invalidated should solve thisnby making the thread break before sending the value to the coroutine.n

revamp default character substitutionsThere's no longer a distinction between Unix and Windows substitutions. Enoughnusers reported problems with Windows-forbidden characters on Samba shares thatnit seems appropriate to make all filenames Windows-safe, even on Unix. Users whonreally want those additional characters (<>:?*|) can re-enable them via thenreplace option. Nobody has complained about beets being *too* conservative.nnThis also adds sanitization of control characters, which is an all-around goodnidea, and the substitution now runs in the Unicode (rather than byte) domain.n

%aunique: use a single field instead of a sequenceFor a less cumbersome uniquifying string, only a single field value is now usedninstead of a prefix of a list of fields. The old semantics had two problems thatnmade it both unnecessary and insufficient:n- In the vast majority of cases, a single field suffices (year OR label ORn  catalog number, for example) and forcing the string to include many identicaln  fields is unnecessary.n- If the albums are very similar, a prefix may be insufficient; a bettern  solution may be found with an arbitrary subset. (Of course, we can't afford ton  search the whole power set.)nSo we're going with a single field for now. This should cause far lessnconfusion.n

add %aunique to default path formats (#190)At this point, everything's in place except for the import workflow. Albumndirectory uniquification works if you import two identically-named albums andnthen immediately execute beet move. Currently, however, a couple of thingsnprevent this from working as expected during the normal import process:n- The tmpl_aunique method expects the item to be associated with an album in then  database before it is called. This is currently not the case.n- With the multithreaded importer, it's possible for both duplicates to haven  their destinations calculated before either is added to the database. Thisn  means that neither will detect a duplicate at the time of the move/copy.n- Even if the above issue is resolved, it will be the case that only the secondn  album to be imported will have a uniquifying string added. If we want to addn  the string to the old album, we'll need to explicitly move it.nAlso, documentation on this feature is still forthcoming.n

The apply_choices coroutine now executes two database transactions per task.nThis has a couple of benefits:n- %aunique{} requires album structures to be in place before the destination()n  call, so this now works as expected.n- As an added bonus, the in_album parameter to move() and destination() --n  along with its associated ugly hacks -- is no longer required.n

transaction objects to control DB accessIn an attempt to finally address the longstanding SQLite locking issues, I'mnintroducing a way to explicitly, lexically scope transactions. The Transactionnclass is a context manager that always fully fetches after SELECTs andnautomatically commits on exit. No direct access to the library is allowed, sonall changes will eventually be committed and all queries will be completed. Thisnwill also provide a debugging mechanism to show where concurrent transactionsnare beginning and ending.nnTo support composition (transaction reentrancy), an internal, per-Library stacknof transactions is maintained. Commits only happen when the outermostntransaction exits. This means that, while it's possible to introduce atomicitynbugs by invoking Library methods outside of a transaction, you can convenientlyncall them *without* a currently-active transaction to get a single atomicnaction.nnNote that this transaction stack concepts assumes a single Library object pernthread. Because we need to duplicate Library objects for concurrent access duento sqlite3 limitation already, this is fine for now. Later, the interface shouldnprovide one transaction stack per thread for shared Library objects.n

exclusive database access (GC-399)This is the crux of the matter. This new lock synchronizes accesses to thendatabase itself, allowing only one thread to have transactions active at a time.nIn effect, this makes sure that beets only has one SQLite transaction active atna time (and is very conservative in this effort; no read sharing is allowedneither). This prevents all contention in SQLite and hides the pathologicalnHAVE_SLEEP=0 behavior.n

Windows: represent paths as UTF-8 internallyWhen we store paths in the database, we always use bytestrings for consistency.nBut on Windows, these paths are converted back to Unicode before they reach thenFS API. This means that the codec used internally is immaterial.nnHowever, we were naively using sys.getfilesystemencoding() for this internalnrepresentation. On Windows, this is MBCS, a broken encoding that can't representnall of Unicode. This change replaces that with UTF-8, a real codec.nnThe decoding bit now tries UTF-8 and falls back to MBCS for compatibility withnexisting databases. The reality, however, is that existing databases may notnwork with this change -- a byte string may represent something different innUTF-8 from what it represents in MBCS. So users should recreated their DBs ifnanything goes wrong.n

misc. minor fixes for artresizer (#64)- Safer proxy resize. The URL parameters are now properly encoded. And an  spurious additional request has been removed.n- Removed manual search of $PATH. Invoking convert without a path does thisn  automatically.n- More pyflakes-friendly test import of PIL.n- Do not delete the NamedTemporaryFile -- doing so creates a race conditionn  where the file might be created between the filename generation and the tooln  invocation.n

artresizer (#64): helper functions, not classesThe previous method was to change self.__class__ dynamically to make __init__ninstantiate different classes. This new way, which uses bare functions insteadnof separate functor-like classes, instead just forwards the resize() call tona module-global implementation based on self.method.nnAdditionally, the semantics of ArtResizer have changed. Clients now *always*ncall resize() and proxy_url(), regardless of method. The method makes *one* ofnthese a no-op. This way, clients need not manually inspect which method isnbeing used.n

fetchart fixes for image resizing (#64)Fixed a number of issues with the changes to fetchart:n- Remove redundant fetches. This was making the Amazon source download everyn  image twice even when art resizing was not enabled!n- Restore local_only switch in plugin hook, which got lost in the shuffle atn  some point.n- Don't replace the original image file in-place; use a temporary file instead.n  This would clobber the original source image on the filesystem with then  downscaled version!n
fix art tests for new URL interface (#64)The various source helper functions now return URLs instead of callingn_fetch_image themselves.n

fetchart: fix command & use maxwidth (#64)An earlier commit broke the call to art_for_album here (too few arguments).nI've also now propagated the maxwidth setting for the command to match thenimport hook.n

lazily initialize ArtResizer singleton (#64)Searching for `convert` or PIL has non-negligible performance overhead, so it'snpreferable to only do it when really necessary. This way, the search is onlynperformed when ArtResizer.shared is accessed for the first time.n
don't use subprocess.check_outputThis function was added in Python 2.7 and we're currently targetting 2.6 as anminimum version. Replaced with a function in util.n
artresizer: fix argument lists to helper functionsAlso added some useful debug logs.n

add extension for proxied images`urllib.urlretrieve` was using the correct extension in most cases -- I thinknwhen the URL ended with .jpg -- but not in every case. This was leading to filesnnamed just cover and not cover.jpg or something else sensible. Innparticular, proxied URLs don't have .jpg extensions. This generates the filenamenmanually so the source image always has an extension.n

documentation for convert.exe problem (#64)We currently just document the fact that convert.exe can interfere with findingnImageMagick's convert binary. We can solve this with a config option easily oncenconfit is merged.nnThis also changes the line endings for fetchart.rst back to Unix.n

Windows: fix relative paths in normpath()The changes introduced in rc1 caused paths to be syspath-ified before they werenpassed to os.path.abspath. The magic prefix caused them to be interpreted asnabsolute paths even if they were relative. The fix is, in this *isolated*ncase, to use Unicode but prefix-free paths in calls to the os.path.* functions.nThose functions need to act on Unicode objects but seem to be purely syntacticn-- nothing is tripped up by using long filenames without the magic prefix.n

Improved multi-disc album detection.- Remove part, volume, vol. multi-disc markers. These are oftenn  part of album titles, and not necessarily indicative of a multi-discn  album. Only look for CD X and disc X (case insensitive), ignoringn  white space and other non-word characters.nn- Don't only expect each disc to be in a subdirectory of a common parentn  directory, with all siblings belonging to the same release. Also matchn  any consecutive siblings (even when the parent contains other albums)n  that are named with the same prefix and multi-disc marker.nn- The `albums_in_dir(path)` function now always yields a list of pathsn  along with each list of items. `ItemTask.path` is now always a list ofn  paths.nn- The `displayable_path(path)` function now accepts a list of paths, andn  will join them with ;  by default. This can be changed with then  `separator` argument.nn- The `sorted_walk()` function now does a case insensitive sort onn  directories, but still returns case sensitive results. This allowsn  better multi-disc album detection.nn- The `art_for_album()` function now takes a list of paths as its secondn  argument, instead of a single path.n

mbsync: split album/item functions; shorter txnsThe main change here is to use shorter transactions -- one per matching entityn-- rather than one large one. This avoids very long transactions when thennetwork happens to move slowly.n

mbsync: use ID lookups instead of full match logicThis change uses _album_for_id and _track_for_id instead of the fullnautotag.match.* functions. It also won't, fornexample, use acoustic fingerprinting even if the chroma plugin is installed.nnFinally, this change catches the error case in which MBIDs are erroneous. mbsync: avoid spurious stores/movesAs _print_and_apply_changes itself does for items, we now shortcutnmodifications (metadata and filesystem) for albums when no changes arenrequired for a given album. This avoids effectively doing a beet move on annalbum even when nothing has changed.n

refactor: everything is like a plugin query (#214)The initial idea for this refactor was motivated by the need to makenPluginQuery.match() have the same method signature as the match() methods onnother queries. That is, it needed to take an *item*, not the pattern andnvalue. (The pattern is supplied when the query is constructed.) So it madensense to move the value-to-pattern code to a class method.nnBut then I realized that all the other FieldQuery subclasses needed to donessentially the same thing. So I eliminated PluginQuery altogether andnrefactored FieldQuery to subsume its functionality. I then changed all thenother FieldQuery subclasses to conform to the same pattern.nnThis has the side effect of allowing different kinds of queries (evennnon-field queries) down the road.n

Add `discogs` plugin, which extends the autotagger to include results from the discogs database.This is a refactor of the plugin developed by `imenem`.nn- Pass `artist`, `album` and `va_likely` to `candidates()` so thatn  plugins don't have to work this out from `items` all over again.n- Pass `artist` and `title` to `item_candidates()`.n- Silence spurious `urllib3` info log lines.n- Use a proper beets user agent with `discogs_client`.n- Remove `abstract_search` plugin. It seems unnecessary. How manyn  music databases are there? How many will beets support? How muchn  common code might there be between them? We can add some abstractionn  if or when more databases are supported.n- Derive more AlbumInfo and TrackInfo properties from discogs Releasen  objects, especially album ID so that beets doesn't just use the firstn  release and think all subsequent releases are duplicates.n- Add basic documentation, doc strings and code comments.n- Sanitise search query. Remove non-word characters and medium info thatn  might filter out good search results.n- Use artist `join` strings from discogs Release object when an albumn  or track has multiple artists.n- Don't rely on discogs track position, which is unreliable. But tracksn  are in order, so we can recalculate medium and medium_index as long asn  we can extract a consistent medium across tracks from the position.n- Add various as a known signal to indicate various artists.n- Prevent `chroma` plugin from returning a a huge track distance for anyn  track that is missing an ID (e.g. all discog tracks).n- `TrackInfo.index` should be the release index (calculated by beets),n  not the medium index (derived from discogs track position).n- Add `AlbumInfo.data_source`. It's Unknown by default which is shownn  in red when displaying a suggested or selected match. The built inn  auto tagger sets it to MusicBrainz which is shown in green. Anythingn  else (e.g. Discogs) is shown in yellow.n- Remove double spaces from album titles (bad data from Discogs).n

Merge pull request #284 from mrmachine/ui-improvementsUI improvements and consistency. Colorisation, indentation, position by importance, and highlight benign changes.rnrn1. Consistently colorise parenthesis surrounding colorised text that is conditional (doesn't always appear) so that it stand out more. This includes the album info data source (when it's not MusicBrainz), the album disambiguation (sometimes there is none), and the partial match message.rnrn2. Indent the album title when there isn't a change. Makes it stand out more from the file path(s) above and info line below, and is consistent with the indentation when there is an album or artist change.rnrn3. When listing releases, colorise album disambiguation in light gray to distinguish it more clearly from the album title. Light gray seems like a good colour because it is subtle, and disambiguation is supplementary information (not green/success, red/error or yellow/warning).rnrn4. Also when listing releases, display similarity before partial message and disambiguation last. This is in order of importance, and also similarity is always present while the others are conditional, and finally it is often the case where the album title is the same and only the disambiguation is different. Using this order keeps things lined up in this case and easier to visually compare similarity and disambiguation text.rnrn5. Colorise benign track index changes (to/from per disc numbering) in yellow, without applying a match penalty. We should still display these because even though the track number is still correct/equivalent, beets will apply a change if the new tags are applied.rnrn6. Don't display source unless it's not MusicBrainz. By default beets will only find matches in the MusicBrainz database. Use a Distance object instead of floats for distance calculations.The new Distance object knows how to perform various types of distancencalculations (expression, equality, number, priority, string).nnIt will keep track of each individual penalty that has been applied sonthat we can utilise that information in the UI and when making decisionsnabout the recommendation level.nnWe now display the top 3 penalties (sorted by weight) on the releasenlist (and ... if there are more than 3), and we display all penaltiesnon the album info line and track change line.nnThe implementation of the `max_rec` setting has been simplified bynremoving duplicate validation and instead looking at the penalties thatnhave been applied to a distance. As a result, we can now configure anmaximum recommendation for any penalty that might be applied.nnWe have a few new checks when calculating album distance:nn`match: preferred: countries` and `match: preferred: media` can each benset to a list of countries and media in order of your preference. Thesenare empty by default. A value that matches the first item will have nonpenalty, and a value that doesn't match any item will have an unweightednpenalty of 1.0.nnIf `match: preferred: original_year` is set to yes, beets will applynan unweighted penalty of 1.0 for each year of difference between thenrelease year and the original year.nnWe now configure individual weights for `mediums` (disctotal), `label`,n`catalognum`, `country` and `albumdisambig` instead of a single genericn`minor` weight. This gives more control, but more importantly separatesnand names the applied penalties so that the UI can convey exactly whichnfields have contributed to the overall distance penalty.nnLikewise, `missing tracks` and `unmatched tracks` are penalised andndisplayed in the UI separately, instead of a combined `partial` penalty.nnDisplay non-MusicBrainz source in the disambiguation string, andnsource in the list of penalties if a release is penalised for beingna non-MusicBrainz.n

drop flexattr namespacesNamespaces were a worthy idea, but they added a lot of complexity to both thenlibrary code itself and every client of the flexattrs interfaces. Getting ridnof them, and having one flat namespace of both traditional fields andnflexattrs, has one huge benefit: we can promote flexattrs to real attributesn(and vice versa) without code changes in every client.nnThis frees us to have a somewhat less efficient implementation of flexattrsnbecause we have a smooth upgrade path for making attributes more efficient vianpromotion.n

introducing slow queriesIn preparation for enabling queries over flexattrs, this is a new path thatnlets queries avoid generating SQLite expressions altogether. Any query thatncan be completely evaluated in SQLite will be, but when it can't, we now fallnback to running the entire query in Python by selecting everything from thendatabase and running the `match` predicate.nnTo begin with, this mechanism replaces RegisteredFieldQueries, whichnpreviously used Python callbacks for evaluation. Now they just indicate thatnthey're slow queries and the query system falls back automatically.nnThis has the great upside that it lets use implement arbitrarily complexnqueries without shoehorning everything into SQLite when that (a) is way tooncomplicated and (b) doesn't buy us much performance anyway. The obviousndrawback is that any code dealing with queries now has to handle two casesn(slow and fast).nnIn the future, we could optimize this further by combing fast and slow querynstyles. For example, if you want to match with a substring *and* a regularnexpression, we can do a first pass in SQLite and apply the regex predicate onnthe results. Avoided for now because premature optimization, etc., etc.nnNext step: implement flexattr matches as slow queries.n
flexible attributes as slow queriesQueries over flexible attributes now Just Work!n
new FlexModel base classI intend to use this for both Item and Album to avoid code duplication andnsimplify code that uses both entities.n
kill BaseAlbumI added this back when I thought I would implement a different subclass thatnrepresented iPods. That means I wrote this code when I had a lime iPod mini. Inam old.n

flexattrs work for AlbumsA second base class, LibModel, maintains a reference to the Library and shouldntake care of database-related tasks like load and store. This is the beginningnof the end of the terrible incongruity between Item and Album objects (onlynthe latter had a library reference). More refactoring to come.nnOne large side effect: Album objects no longer automatically storenmodifications. You have to call album.store(). Several places in the codenassume otherwise; they need cleaning up.nnResultIterator is now polymorphic (it takes a type parameter, which must be ansubclass of LibModel).n

Specify configuration behaviour with testsBeets stores all its data in the `BEETSDIR` directory. The default isndetermined by the system:nn* `%APPDATA%beets` on Windows. If the `APPDATA` environment variable isn  not set it falls back to `~AppDataRoamingbeets`.n* `$XDG_CONFIG_DIR/beets` on UNIX. If the `XDG_CONFIG_DIR` environmentn  variable is not set it falls back to `~/.config/beets`n* `~/Library/Application Support/beets` on OSXnnThe default can be overwritten using the `BEETSDIR` environment variable.nnThe user configuration is read from `$BEETSDIR/config.yaml`. Additionalnconfiguration files that overwrite options from the user configuration maynbe specified using the `--config` command line options.nnAll relative paths in any configuration are resolved relative to `BEETSDIR`.n

Remove date packing and invert date dependencyBefore, each year, month, and day field used packing to store its values in thensame tag but at different positions. We then instantiated an`CompositeDateField` to combine the different values. This lead to codenduplication in the storage styles for these fields. It also inverted the datandependency. It's more natural to think of year, month, and day as part of andate then as of a date as composed of these.nnNow, only `DateField` class stores data in the files tag. This makes sense: Onentag, one field that accesses it. To obtain access to the year, month, and daynparts, the DateField is equipped with factories that create `DateItemField`ninstances associated to a `DateField`. These descriptor allow us to get and setnparts of a date field.n

Make _formatted_mapping lazy and an instanceThe motivation for this is to increase the performance of template evalutation.nnPreviously, the `model._formatted_mapping()` method returned a dictionary thatnserved as the environment (mapping of variable names to values) when evaluatingna template. To populate the dictionary, we iterated over all keys in the model,nformatted the values, and assigned it to the dictionary. This meant wenformatted every field, even if the template did not require it.nnWith this commit `_formatted_mapping()` does not return a populated dictionarynbut a proxy (or view) instance. The object only knows about the model and thenkeys it provides the formatted view for. If a variable is requested by thentemplate it computes the formatted value on the fly.nnThe class-based approach has one additional advantage: In the future, we cannseparate the formatting logic from the database logic.n

dbcore.Results: Avoid duplicate constructionIterating over a results set multiple times should not take the same amountneach time. We now keep around the materialized objects and re-use them withniteration. This solves a performance problem in the `play` plugin, which usesnlen(results) multiple times and was therefore taking an unnecessarynperformance hit when the query was slow.n

Refactor ftintitle to extract the code to find the featured artistThis removes the code that extracts the featured artist from thenoriginal artist field from the ft_in_title function and puts it into itsnown.nnIt also adds a custom ArtistNotFoundException that find_feat_part willnthrow if the album artist is not in the artist field.nnThis allows us to easily test the results of finding a featured artistnin the artist sting, and thus adds tests for the usual test cases thatnthe split_on_feat gets tested for.n

Fix a bug in ftintitle with the order of album artistThere was a bug in the find_feat_part function that would cause it tonfail if the album artist was the second part of the featured string.nnFor example, if the Artist field was Alice & Bob, and the Album Artistnfield was Bob it would return None due to the order.nnThis fixes that and adds test cases to ensure it doesn't return.n

Make list(ui.config) raise a TypeErrorAs per PEP234 (https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0234/) if an objectnhas __getitem__() but not __iter__() then the former will be used tonbuild an iterable, invoking it with 0, then 1, ... until a KeyError isnraised. Lazy configuration makes it never happen, and list(config) runsnindefinitely, hogging all memory.nnImplement __iter__(), which raises a TypeError, to solve that problem.n

Improve repr(ConfigView): fix class name displayedUse config.__class__.__name__ instead of ConfigView in __repr__().nnBefore:n>>> from beets import uin>>> cn<ConfigView: root>n>>> c['foo']n<ConfigView: foo>nnAfter:n>>> from beets import uin>>> cn<LazyConfig: root>n>>> c['foo']n<Subview: foo>n

fetchart complains if no imaging backend availableThe `enforce_ratio` and `minwidth` options depend on PIL or ImageMagick.nPreviously it silently fails. Now it will log a warning, and accept thenimage.nnTests concerning these options are skipped when no imaging backend is available.nnFix #1460n

fetchart: improve Wikipedia art sourceArtists with non-typical casing (e.g., alt-J, dEUS) would not get matched onnDBPedia, as the RDFS:label uses arbitrary casing, and SPARQL provides only exactnmatches. The FOAF:name attribute is always title-cased (e.g., Alt-J, Deus).nnDue to a bug in DBPedia, the cover filename is truncated when it containsnparentheses, (e.g., 'Foo bar (band).jpg' gets truncated to 'Foo bar .jpg').nTo work around this, an additional Wikipedia call gets made for all itsnimages, in which we try to match our truncated image.nnThe Wikipedia art source now catches the correct exceptions, instead ofna broad catch-all.nnWikipedia album images can be gifs, so these are now added to the list ofnaccepted content types.n

add merging functionality to duplicates pluginThis patch depends on %aunique not being present in config.pathsnfor behavior as intended.nnThe logic surrounding moving/copying a track from a duplicated album tonthe original one could probably be extracted out and put intonlibrary.Album.nnThis is based on the ordering imposed by the tiebreaking facilitynintroduced in 6be98b0a369aa148acee8906d55076ac824b5108. Once a naturalnduplicate ordering is in place, then the strategies for merging are:nnItems:nnIterate through each available field:nIterate through each duplicate:nIf current duplicate has a field not set in the original, set it therenBreaknnAlbums:nnIterate through each duplicate:nIterate through each item in duplicate:nIf current item is not present in original, copy it therenContinuen

Log more details about duplicatesPart of the investigation into #1652.n

Roll back PR #1358: regression on recent duplicateThis should fix #1652, which found that this code did the wrong thing whennthere were *no* `found_duplicates`: that is, when the duplicate actually camenfrom the `seen_keys` list, so the album is not in the database yet. Thisnhandling was confusing no non-empty duplicates with no in-databasenduplicates, and incorrectly bypassing the duplicates prompt.nnSince having empty albums in the database is a rare case (it should benimpossible!), and we should no longer *crash* when it happens, I amnconsidering it unnecessary to handle it specially. The user will now just seenOld: 0 items and that's that.n

Importer: no separate stage for applying metadataIt's cheaper and easier to just apply metadata in the UI thread. Thenadvantage, then, is that we no longer need to keep track of anything in-memorynto enumerate data that has been seen by the user but not added to the databasenyet!nnIn the next step, I'll remove `seen_idents` altogether.n

Remove `seen_idents` setThis was used since time immemorial to keep track of recently-imported musicnthat hasn't hit the database yet. I created it when the importer only addednmusic to the database at the end of the pipeline, after doing all the work tonmanipulate the metadata. Now, for several reasons, we add the musicnimmediately after the user sees it and then manipulate the records *in thendatabase*. With the latest change, which gets rid of the last separationnbetween UI and database-adding, we no longer need to do this.n

convert plugin: fix braces in filenames causing tracebacks in pretend modePreviously pretend mode (a.k.a. dry run mode) passed the command to benprinted directly to _log.info, whose first argument is technically anformat string. Thus the command string was parsed for replacement fields, suchnas '{foo}', which could cause the format evaluation to fail if the filenamesncontained in the command contained valid (or partially valid) replacement fields.nnThis fix simply inserts an argument '{0}' to the call to _log.info, which is anformat string that simply evaluates to the second argument to _log.info (thencommand string). By doing this, the command string is not parsed for replacementnfields.n

Rename `InvalidQueryArgumentTypeError` to `InvalidQueryArgumentValueError`The way we use `InvalidQueryArgumentTypeError` is more akin to a `ValueError` than a `TypeError`. Always use specific null values for fixed fieldsThis came out of an attempt to address the mysterious testing problems fromnPR #2563 and turned into a big old debacle. As it turns out, the problem camenfrom calling Item.from_path and getting None for fields that weren't fillednout by the MediaFile data. Everywhere else, we fill out these fixed attributesnwith the special null value for the field's type, so it's actually prettynconfusing that these could mysteriously become None. I think it will be sanernall around if we enforce this universally.nnThere were two possible fixes: one in __getitem__ to check for missing valuesnand one that set all the missing values in the constructor. I opted for thenformer because it has a smaller footprint, but the latter might have slightlynbetter performance (depending on the ratio of constructions to lookups).n
Fix some brittle query testsThese were written to incidentally depend on Nones; the behavior they'renactually testing doesn't really have anything to say about None-ness.n

Explicitly let artpath be missingWe really want `Album.artpath` to be None sometimes, and this was relying onnsome accidental dbcore behavior before. Now, we explicitly mark the field asnnullable: it may be a path, or it may be None to indicate that there is nonart.n
Fix ipfs test to sort items in order
Musical key field may be NoneFixes a `modify` test, of all things.n

Fixes #1210: Skip non-audio tracks from MusicBrainzThis ignores non-audio tracks during import:n- Data tracks, based on their title `[data track]` (which seems to benthe MusicBrainz convention, as there's no specific flag to indicatenthat a track is a data one),n- Video tracks, based on the `video=true` attribute.nnIt's similar to the Picard changes mentioned in #1210, except it doesn'tndeal with `[silence]` tracks: These ones will probably require a settingnto let the user control if they should be imported or not.n

But fornalbums with invalid track MBID that happens to be the first track,nMusicBrainz changes won't be applied to whole album, only whosentracks with valid MBID. This is particularly annoying since thosenchanges are actually displayed for every `beet mbsync` run, but nevernget applied.nnFix this issue by finding any track that get MusicBrainz updates, andnapply it to whole album.n

playlist: Add playlist pluginAdds M3U playlist support as a query to beets and thus partiallynresolves issue #123. The implementation is heavily based on #2380 bynRobin McCorkell.nnIt supports referencing playlists by absolute path:nn$ beet ls playlist:/path/to/someplaylist.m3unnIt also supports referencing playlists by name. The playlist is thennseached in the playlist_dir and the .m3u extension is appended to thenname:nn$ beet ls playlist:anotherplaylistnnThe configuration for the plugin looks like this:nnplaylist:nrelative_to: librarynplaylist_dir: /path/to/playlistsnnThe relative_to option specifies how relative paths in playlists arenhandled. By default, paths are relative to the library directory. Itnalso possible to make them relative to the playlist or set the optionnor set it to a fixed path.n

BPD tests: add basic test frameworkA simple TCP client wraps the low level protocol to allow testing of thenBPD server as a black box.n
BPD tests: password command

BPD tests: check all specified commands knownThe current MPD spec is several versions ahead of BPD. These tests justncompare the full specified list of commands against what BPD claims tonsupport (without actually testing their implementations). It's handy asna measure of progress against the specification, but can perhaps bendropped later once all of the individual protocol methods have tests.n
BPD tests: run BPD Server with a fake gstplayer

BPD tests: test supported tag typesMPD now supports more fields (tags) than what BPD advertises. Fixingnthis should be a simple task of extending the mapping of fields to tagsnin BPD's implementation.n

BPD tests: test helper for BPD batch commandsThe MPD protocol allows batching commands. There are two choices for thenfirst message that announced a batch is starting, and we just go for thenone that causes the server to respond with a marker message between eachnindividual response, since that's easier. This might need to be tweakednin order to test the behaviour with the other batch indicator.n
BPD tests: test several simple commands

Add a DummyIn::close no-op implementationThe BOD tests are currently forking a process with a server running, andnthis attempts to close stdin. Tests were failing due to DummyIn notnimplementing the close() method. Adding this simple no-op does the tricknto allow forking and seems like a harmless addition.n
BPD tests: fix CI failures

BPD tests: improve test helpersDecode the bytes to strings: the MPD protocol specifies that thencommunications are all in UTF-8.nnAlso parse the body into a dict since this is typically more convenientnthan having to do it manually in each test.n

Changelog for #3202
bpd: separate tests by command category

bpd: fix crossfade commandAlthough crossfade is not implemented in bpd, we can store the settingnand repeat is back to clients. Also log a warning that the operation isnnot implemented.nnThe real MPD doesn't show the crossfade in status if it's zero sincenthat means no crossfade, so now we don't either.n

bpd: error instead of crashing on extra argumentIf an MPC client is expecting a command to take an argument that bpdnisn't expecting (e.g. because of a difference in protocol versions) thennbpd currently crashes completely. Instead, do what the real MPD does andnreturn an error message over the protocol.n

bpd: add mixramp commandsThese are a more sophisticated version of crossfade so we're free tonignore them, at least for now. We now track the values of the twonsettings, and show them in the status output. Like MPD, we suppress thenmixrampdb value if it's set to nan, which is how it signals that thenfeature should be turned off.n

bpd: add dummy command for volumeMPD supports a deprecated command 'volume' which was used to change thenvolume by a relative amount unlike its replacement 'setvol' which usesnan absolute amount. As far as I can tell 'volume' always responds with a systemnerror message No mixer.n

bpd: add replay_gain_* commandsThere's a special status command for checking the replay gain mode,nwhich can be set to one of a short list of possible values. For now atnleast we can ignore this feature, but track the setting anyway.n
bpd: support consume command

bpd: no-op support for persistent playlistsThe real MPD offers persistent playlist manipulation, storing thenplaylists in a directory set in the config file. If that directory isnnot available then the feature is disabled and the relevant commands allnrespond with errors. Based on this, the initial support in bpd justnreturns errors matching the MPD server in the disabled mode.nnFor playlistadd, extend the _bpd_add helper to work with playlists othernthan the queue in order to support testing the real implementations ofnthese commands in the future.n

bpd: support the single commandThis command instructs bpd to stop playing when the current songnfinishes. In the MPD 0.20 protocol this flag gains a value 'oneshot' butnfor now we just support its older version with a boolean value.n
bpd: test fields returned by status command

bpd: fix repeat mode behaviourThe repeat flag indicates that the entire playlist should be repeated.nIf both the repeat and single flags are set then this triggers the oldnbehaviour of looping over a single track.n

bpd: fix bug in bounds check of current song indexThe songs are indexed starting from zero for the play command, howevernthe bound check was off by one. An index matching the length of thenplaylist would crash the server instead of responding with an errornmessage over the protocol.n

bpd: skipping backwards through zero keeps playingPreviously issuing the 'previous' command when at position 0 on thenplaylist would cause bpd to stop playing. MPD instead just restarts thencurrently playing song instead, so we now match this behaviour.n
bpd: fix repeat, consume and single in reverseThese flags are all relevant to the 'previous' command as well as then'next' command.n
use most simple syntax

bpd: improve exception handlingCheck function signature instead of using TypeError to crudely guessnthat the wrong number of arguments were provided.nnPrevent bpd from crashing when trying to log a traceback. Then`traceback.format_exc` function takes an optional argument which isnsupposed to be an integer restricting the length of the backtrace tonshow. Instead we were passing the exception object to this function andncausing a new exception to be raised.n
bpd: return real audio data
Fix beets.util.inspect for Python 3Under the original compatibility shim we weren't correctly inclusingn`self` in the argument list for bound methods.n

bpd: track and log client session detailsKeep track of a list of currently-connected clients.nnUse `socket.getpeername()` to get an identifier for each connection andninclude this in each log message. This function is documented as notnbeing available on all systems, but it's unclear which systems thisninvolves.nnAlso log a message on client connect and disconnect events. If thendisconnection reason is because the client sent a blank line, match MPDnby returning a protocol error then hanging up. Escape curly braces.n

bpd: implement the idle commandGetting this command puts the connection into a special mode where itnawaits MPD events (like the player changing state or the playlistnchanging due to other clients interacting with the server.nnThe MPD specification states that events should queue while a client isnconnected, and when it issues the `idle` command any matching eventsnshould be sent immediately if there are any, or as soon as they happennotherwise.n

bpd: add control socketA new `ControlConnection` is created each time a client connects overna new control socket. This is used to forward events from the player,nand also for debugging utilities that are not part of the real MPDnprotocol.nnThis new feature reuses as much infrastructure from the normal protocolnhandling as possible (e.g. `Command` for parsing messages). While thennormal connection delegates to server `cmd_*` methods which are stringngenerators, the control connections delegate to `ctrl_*` methods definednon the connection itself that are full coroutines.n

tests: avoid non-test classes named Test*When using pytest's test collector, any class with a name starting withnTest is collected. If it notices that the class has an `__init__` membernthen it skips it with a warning since it's probably a false positive.nThis isn't a big deal, but we can avoid warnings like this:nntest/test_ui_importer.py:33n  beets/test/test_ui_importer.py:33: PytestCollectionWarning: cannot collect test class 'TestTerminalImportSession' because it has a __init__ constructornclass TestTerminalImportSession(TerminalImportSession):nnsimply by renaming TestX to XFixture.n

bluelet: catch ECONNRESETWhen ncmpcpp quits after an error it causes a connection reset by peernexception, also known as ECONNRESET (104) in errno terms. Allow other ReplayGain backends to support R128.Previously using EBU R128 forced the use of the bs1770gain backend.nThis change adds a whitelist of backends supporting R128. When the configurednbackend is in that list it will also be used for R128 calculations. Otherwisenbs1770gain is still used as a default.nnThis should not change the overall behaviour of the program at all, but allownfor further R128-supporting backends to be added.n

replaygain: add ffmpeg backendAdd replaygain backend using ffmpeg's ebur128 filter.nnThe album gain is calculated as the mean of all BS.1770 gating block powers.nBesides differences in gating block offset, this should be equivalent to anBS.1770 analysis of a proper concatenation of all tracks.nnJust calculating the mean of all track gains (as implemented by the bs1770gainnbackend) yields incorrect results as that would:n- completely ignore track lengthsn  - just using length in seconds won't work either (e.g. BS.1770 ignoresnpassages below a threshold)n- take the mean of track loudness, not powernnWhen using the ffmpeg replaygain backend to create R128_*_GAIN tags, thentargetlevel will be set to -23 LUFS. GitHub PullRequest #3065 will make thisnconfigurable.nIt will also skip peak calculation, as there is no R128_*_PEAK tag.nnIt is checked if the libavfilter library supports replaygain calculation. Beforenversion 6.67.100 that did require the `--enable-libebur128` compile-time-option,nafter that the ebur128 library is included in libavfilter itself. Thus wenrequire either a recent enough libavfilter version or the `--enable-libebur128`noption.n
